beta-mode:
==========

Too slow. Possible solutions:

1. Base indentation on previous line. Only lines beginning a construct, 
   ending a construct or special in other ways should be indented differently.
   lynbech is working on a version.

2. Make limits in searchs:

   In beta-indent-line:

   (let (limit (if beta-search-distance
                   (max (- (point) beta-search-distance) 0)
                   0))
      ...
      (beta-beginning-of-construct .... limit)
      ...)

3. Conditional inclusion of beta-menu/beta-hilit using

(defun version-description-of-emacs ()
  "Returns a list `(FLAVOR MAJOR MINOR)' describing this Emacs instance.
FLAVOR can be `GNU', `Lucid' or `Epoch', MAJOR and MINOR are the major
and minor release numbers."
  (let* ((flavor
          (cond ((boundp 'epoch::version)
                 'Epoch)
                ((string-match "Lucid" emacs-version)
                 'Lucid)
                (t 'GNU)))
         (emacs-version
          (if (eq flavor 'Epoch) "18.59" emacs-version))
         (major-version
          (if (string-match "\\([0-9]+\\)\\.\\([0-9]+\\)" emacs-version)
              (car (read-from-string
                    emacs-version
                    (match-beginning 1)
                    (match-end 1)))))
         (minor-version
          (if major-version
              (car (read-from-string
                    emacs-version
                    (match-beginning 2)
                    (match-end 2))))))
    (list flavor major-version minor-version)))

4) Error in comment indentation

Du har ret. Det er parentesen efter "for" inde i kommentaren, der }benbart
forvirrer beta-mode. Kommer p} listen.
 
    // gram.thisObject then (* always this(P) *)
       ad.son->rDen;
           (* 'on' is adjusted during checking to avoid (for ...for) etc. *)
 
5) Error in comment handling

Her er en lille uhensigtsm{ssighed ved BETAs Emacs mode. Hvis man 
skriver
 
   (*________
 
(hvor _'erne angiver et antal mellemrum, inkl. 0)
 
og taster }, er resulatetet
 
   (________*)
 
hvilket ikke er en lovlig kommentar.

6) infinate GC

Jeg kan f} Emacs' BETA-mode til at g} i uendelig l|kke, hvis jeg 
skriver one-linere og pr|ver at }bne eller afslutte konstruktioner 
med "{" og "}".
 
Hvis man f.eks. skriver
 
   ORIGIN'~beta/basiclib/v1.4/betaenv' --program:descriptor-- (#
                                                                ^
og stiller cursoren                                             her
 
og taster "}", vil man f} sin "#)", hvorefter Emacs g}r i gang med 
en vanvittig "garbage collection...done"-l|kke. 
 
Hvis man tilsvarende skriver
 
   ORIGIN'~beta/basiclib/v1.4/betaenv' --program:descriptor-- (# #)
 
og stiller cursoren                                             ^her,
 
og taster "{", g}r Emacs igen i GC-l|kke, og denne gang f}r man 
f|rst sin "(#", n}r man taster Ctrl-G.

7)
Hvis man har en variabel

        elseL

saa  gir det ogsaa en underligt resultat, idet emacs tror at det er else
i en if-imp.

8)

TITLE:  beta-compile results in Emacs's beta-mode.el are not "GNU friendly"
 
TEXT: Error output of beta compiler is not GNU emacs friendly, that is CTRL-`
after ALT-x beta-compile would not work: GNU C/C++ generate warning and error
messages containing the line number in the source file, and GNU emacs is able 
to open that file and position the cursor at the beginning of the offending 
line.

9) Typing <return> when placed just before *) in a comment causes
   the cursor to be placed AFTER *) on the new line.

   This is probably caused by the following code at the end of beta-newline:

	(if comment
	    (progn
	      (skip-chars-forward " \t")
	      (if (not (looking-at "\\*")) 
		  (progn 
		    (insert "*")
		    (if (looking-at "\)")
			(forward-char 1)
		      (if beta-space-after-star (insert " ")))
		    (save-excursion (beta-indent-line)))
		(progn
		  (beta-indent-line)
		  (forward-char 1)
		  (if (not (eolp)) (forward-char 1)))))
	  (beta-indent-line)))
